  "text": "We used tree volume estimates (m 3 ha À1 ) for pine (Pinus sylvestris), spruce (Picea abies) and birch (Betula pubescens subsp. pubescens and B. pubescens subsp. czerepanovii treated as one taxon) previously published by [CITATION_1] . The original vegetation database was compiled in 1992-1994 by the National Land Survey of Finland (2002) , which gives the average volume (m 3 ha À1 ) of the growing stock based on field plot data, optical area satellite images and digital maps [CITATION_2] . It specifies tree volume classes at every 25-m Â 25-m grid cell in a 123-km Â 181-km area for the northern plots and in six ca. 20-km Â 20-km for the southern plots. The tree volume classes have been reclassified according to [CITATION_3] to estimate tree volume in each grid cell [CITATION_4] . There have been no dramatic decreases in tree abundance due to fire or felling around the pollen trap sites during the pollen monitoring period, so the plant volume data are assumed to reflect the surrounding vegetation during the whole period .",
